1 46, or 59 thereof, and further excepting G.S. 14-82, 14-145, 14-183, 14-184,
2 14-186, 14-190.9, 14-247, 14-248, or 14-313 thereof, and either of the
3 following conditions is met:
4 a. The offense is committed with the intent to benefit, promote, or further
5 the interests of a criminal gang or for the purposes of increasing a
6 person's own standing or position within a criminal gang.
7 b. The participants in the offense are identified as criminal gang members
8 acting individually or collectively to further any criminal purpose of a
9 criminal gang.collectively.
10 (3) Criminal gang leader or organizer. – Any criminal gang member who acts in
11 any position of management with regard to the criminal gang and who meets
12 two or more at least one of the following criteria:
13 a. Exercises decision-making authority over matters regarding a criminal
14 gang.
15 b. Participates in the direction, planning, organizing, or commission of
16 criminal gang activity.
17 c. Recruits other gang members.
18 d. Receives a larger portion of the proceeds of criminal gang activity.
19 e. Exercises control and authority over other criminal gang
20 members.Supervises or directs the actions of another criminal gang
21 member or members during criminal gang activity.
22 (4) Criminal gang member. – Any person who (i) meets three or more of the
23 following criteria:criteria or (ii) meets at least two of the following criteria,
24 and one of the criteria is sub-subdivision a., b., or c. of this subdivision:
25 a. The person admits to being a member of a criminal gang.
26 b. The person is identified as a criminal gang member by a reliable
27 source, including a parent or a guardian.
28 c. The person is in possession of or linked to a criminal gang by physical
29 evidence, including ledgers, rosters, or membership documents.
30 c.d. The person has been previously involved in criminal gang activity.
31 d.e. The person has adopted symbols, hand signs, or graffiti associated
32 with a criminal gang.
33 e.f. The person has adopted the display of colors or the style of dress
34 associated with a criminal gang.
35 f. The person is in possession of or linked to a criminal gang by physical
36 evidence, including photographs, ledgers, rosters, written or electronic
37 communications, or membership documents.
38 g. The person has tattoos or markings associated with a criminal gang.
39 h. The person has adopted language or terminology associated with a
40 criminal gang.
41 i. The person appears in any form of photographs, social media media,
42 or written or electronic communication to promote a criminal
43 gang.gang or document criminal gang activity."
44 SECTION 2.(b) This section becomes effective December 1, 2026, and applies to
45 offenses committed on or after that date.
46 SECTION 3.(a) G.S. 14-50.17 reads as rewritten:
47 "§ 14-50.17. Soliciting; encouraging participation.
48 (a) It is unlawful for any person to cause, encourage, solicit, or coerce a person 16 18
49 years of age or older to participate in criminal gang activity.
50 (b) A violation of this section is a Class H Class F felony."
51 SECTION 3.(b) G.S. 14-50.18 reads as rewritten:
Page 2 House Bill 1173-Third Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 "§ 14-50.18. Soliciting; encouraging participation; minor.
2 (a) It is unlawful for any person to cause, encourage, solicit, or coerce a person under 16
3 18 years of age to participate in criminal gang activity.
4 (b) A violation of this section is a Class F Class D felony.
5 (c) Nothing in this section shall preclude a person who commits a violation of this section
6 from criminal culpability for the underlying offense committed by the minor under any other
7 provision of law."
8 SECTION 3.(c) This section becomes effective December 1, 2026, and applies to
9 offenses committed on or after that date.
10 SECTION 4.(a) Article 13A of Chapter 14 of the General Statutes is amended by
11 adding a new section to read:
12 "§ 14-50.32. Use, carry, or possess a firearm by a member of a criminal gang in relation to
13 or in furtherance of a drug felony or a crime of violence.
14 (a) For the purposes of this section, the following definitions apply:
15 (1) Brandish. – To display all or part of a firearm or otherwise make the presence
16 of the firearm known to another person.
17 (2) Crime of violence. – A crime where there is a use or threatened use of physical
18 force against the person or property of another or that by its nature involves a
19 substantial risk of physical force against the person or property of another in
20 the course of committing the crime.
21 (3) Drug crime. – Any offense that would be chargeable by indictment under
22 Article 5 of Chapter 90 of the General Statutes.
23 (4) Firearm. – Any (i) weapon, including a starter gun, which will or is designed
24 to or may readily be converted to expel a projectile by the action of an
25 explosive, or its frame or receiver, or (ii) firearm muffler or firearm silencer.
26 This term does not include an antique firearm as defined in G.S. 14-409.11.
27 (b) It shall be unlawful for any member of a criminal gang during and in relation to any
28 crime of violence or drug crime for which the person would be chargeable by indictment under
29 the laws of this State to use, carry, or possess a firearm in furtherance of that crime. A violation
30 of this subsection is a Class G felony, unless subsection (c) or (d) of this section applies.
31 (c) If a firearm is brandished during the commission of the offense, then the violation is
32 a Class F felony.
33 (d) If a firearm is discharged during the commission of the offense, then the violation is
34 a Class D felony."
35 SECTION 4.(b) Article 13A of Chapter 14 of the General Statutes is amended by
36 adding a new section to read:
37 "§ 14-50.33. Sell, deliver, give, or transfer a firearm to a juvenile by a member of a criminal
38 gang.
39 (a) It shall be unlawful for a member of a criminal gang to sell, deliver, give, or otherwise
40 transfer a firearm to a person whom the criminal gang member knows or has reasonable cause to
41 believe is a juvenile. For purposes of this section, the term "juvenile" means a person who is less
42 than 18 years of age.
43 (b) A violation of this section is a Class G felony."
44 SECTION 4.(c) Article 13A of Chapter 14 of the General Statutes is amended by
45 adding a new section to read:
46 "§ 14-50.34. Use of witness testimony.
47 Criminal gang activity, membership, association, leadership, and existence may be proven
48 through the testimony of a fact witness, an expert witness, or a combined fact and expert witness
49 pursuant to Chapter 8C of the General Statutes. In any proceeding pursuant to this Article, expert
50 testimony is admissible to show particular conduct, status, and customs indicative of criminal
51 gangs and criminal gang activity, including any of the following:
House Bill 1173-Third Edition Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) Characteristics of persons who are members of a criminal gang.
2 (2) Specific rivalries between criminal gangs.
3 (3) Common practices and operations of criminal gangs and members of those
4 criminal gangs.
5 (4) Social customs and behavior of members of criminal gangs.
6 (5) Terminology used by members of criminal gangs.
7 (6) Codes of conduct, including criminal conduct, of particular criminal gangs.
8 (7) The types of crimes that are likely to be committed by a particular criminal
9 gang or by criminal gangs in general."
10 SECTION 4.(d) Article 13A of Chapter 14 of the General Statutes is amended by
11 adding a new section to read:
12 "§ 14-50.35. Venue.
13 In any criminal proceeding brought under this Article, the crime shall be construed to have
14 been committed in any county in which any act was performed as part of criminal gang activity."
15 SECTION 4.(e) This section becomes effective December 1, 2026, and applies to
16 offenses committed on or after that date.
17 SECTION 5.(a) Article 4 of Chapter 8C of the General Statutes is amended by
18 adding a new section to read:
19 "Rule 416. Evidence of criminal gang activity.
20 (a) For purposes of this rule, the term "criminal gang activity" is as defined in
21 G.S. 14-50.16A.
22 (b) In any proceeding in which a person is accused of conducting, participating in, or
23 conspiring to commit criminal gang activity, or in any proceeding under Article 13B of Chapter
24 14 of the General Statutes, evidence of the defendant's commission of criminal gang activity may
25 be considered for the purpose of proving any element of the alleged criminal offense.
26 (c) In any proceeding in which the prosecution intends to offer evidence under this rule,
27 the prosecutor shall disclose the evidence to the defendant, including statements of witnesses or
28 a summary of the substance of any testimony that is expected to be offered, at least 10 days in
29 advance of trial, unless the time is shortened or lengthened or pretrial notice is excused by the
30 judge upon good cause shown.
31 (d) This rule shall not be the exclusive means to admit or consider the evidence described
32 in this rule."
33 SECTION 5.(b) This section becomes effective December 1, 2026, and applies to
34 offenses committed on or after that date.
35 SECTION 6.(a) G.S. 15A-1340.16E reads as rewritten:
36 "§ 15A-1340.16E. Enhanced sentence for offenses committed by criminal gang members as
37 a part of criminal gang activity.
38 (a) Except as otherwise provided in subsection (b) of this section, if a person is convicted
39 of any felony other than a Class A, B1, or B2 felony, and it is found that the offense was
40 committed as part of criminal gang activity as defined in G.S. 14-50.16A(2), then the person shall
41 be sentenced at a felony class level one class two classes higher than the principal felony for
42 which the person was convicted.
43 (b) If subsection (a) of this section applies and the person is found to be a criminal gang
44 leader or organizer as defined in G.S. 14-50.16A(3), the person shall be sentenced at a felony
45 class level two three classes higher than the principal felony for which the person was convicted.
46 …."
47 SECTION 6.(b) This section becomes effective December 1, 2026, and applies to
48 offenses committed on or after that date.
49 SECTION 7. Except as otherwise provided, this act is effective when it becomes
50 law.
